- I am writing a technical book in LaTeX. The book is for software engineering students, as an introduction to the variuos concepts.
When generating content:
- Use \section and \subsection for hierarchy.
- Use the listings package for code blocks.
- Always include \label{} for sections and figures so I can cross-reference them.
- Every \chapter, \section, and \figure must have a \label{} using the format type:name (e.g., sec:observer_pattern).
- If I ask for a diagram, use TikZ or PlantUML syntax.
- Prefer \include{} for chapters and \input{} for smaller fragments or TikZ files.
- Always ensure new chapters are added to the main.tex file structure.
- Use \texttt{} for class names, method names, and file paths mentioned in prose.
- Use the listings (or minted) environment for code blocks. Always specify the language (e.g., [language=Java]).
- Maintain a professional, pedagogical tone. Use 'we' to guide the reader through examples.
- If a diagram is needed, default to PlantUML for logic and TikZ for high-precision architectural layouts.
- Reference the custom styles defined in preamble.sty (e.g., arch_box, flow_arrow) rather than defining colors inline.
- Only use standard packages like amsmath, graphicx, hyperref, and cleveref. If you need a new package, ask me to add it to the preamble first.
- Remember to escape special characters like _ or & when they appear in technical text (e.g., user\_id)
- Use biblatex with biber for references.
- Bibliography file is located at references.bib.
- Use \autocite{} for citations.
- Before each code snippet, include a \needspace{} to ensure the code snippet is not breaking across pages.
- Ensure each code snippet is formatted correctly, to use the correct color theme, see example here:
```
\needspace{5\baselineskip}
\begin{ridercode}{Java}
public interface PlaceOrderPort {
    OrderId placeOrder(PlaceOrderCommand command);
}
\end{ridercode}
```
- When referencing patterns or practices, use the \todo{text here} LaTeX command to add a comment about cross-references to be added later.
- When coming up with examples, use the Case.md file to get ideas. 
- All code examples should be formatted according to the CodeFormattingRules.md file.